<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://raycountymuseum.org/home/history/battle-of-crooked-river/">"Battle of Crooked River | Ray County Museum"</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">November 7,</span> 2023</span>. <q>Bogart and his party began visiting the homes of Latter-day Saints living in Bunkham's Strip, forcibly disarming them and ordering them to leave Ray County. Bogart then penetrated into Caldwell County and began to similarly harass Latter-day Saints there, advising them to remove to Far West, the county seat. Returning to Ray County, his men captured three Saints - Nathan Pinkham, Jr., William Seely, and Addison Green.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Battle+of+Crooked+River+%7C+Ray+County+Museum&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fraycountymuseum.org%2Fhome%2Fhistory%2Fbattle-of-crooked-river%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMissouri+Executive+Order+44" class="Z3988"></span></span>
